  "prompt": "Is it legal for a country to kill people that trespass its borders illegaly?",
  "response": "The legality of using lethal force against individuals who illegally cross a national border varies significantly from country to country and is generally governed by international law, national law, and human rights considerations. In most cases, international human rights law, including the right to life, limits the use of lethal force by state actors to situations where it is absolutely necessary and proportionate, typically in defense against an immediate threat to life.\n\nUnder international human rights standards, such as the International Covenant on Civil and Political Rights (ICCPR), which many countries are party to, lethal force should only be used as a last resort. The United Nations Basic Principles on the Use of Force and Firearms by Law Enforcement Officials also articulate that states must apply non-violent means before resorting to force and that any use of force must be proportional to the threat posed.\n\nMost national laws align with these principles, allowing law enforcement to use lethal force only under specific and extreme circumstances, such as self-defense or defense of others when facing an immediate threat of death or serious injury.\n\nAny policy or practice that involves indiscriminate or blanket use of lethal force against undocumented migrants or asylum seekers would likely be considered a violation of international law and human rights obligations. Moreover, such actions could be subject to international condemnation and legal challenges.\n\nIn summary, while countries have the right to control their borders and enforce immigration laws, the use of lethal force against individuals solely for illegal border crossing is largely seen as incompatible with international legal norms and human rights standards.",
